Title : Luis Kemnitzer
Text : {{for|the artist|Luis Camnitzer}}

[[File:Luis Kemnitzer.jpg|right|thumb|Kemnitzer wearing his Grammy Award medal]]

'''Luis Stowell<ref name=Grads>[https://books.google.com/books?id=fvs4AQAAMAAJ&pg=RA5-PA69&lpg=RA5-PA69&dq=Luis+Kemnitzer&source=bl&ots=eckaoLs_SA&sig=jzdydOjPyexjcHlwh8ZJX10bmeQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjht6bHt-zQAhUGwWMKHeNsBx4Q6AEIhAEwGg#v=onepage&q=Luis%20Kemnitzer&f=false University of California Register, 1954-1955, with Announcements for 1955-1956, IN TWO VOLUMES: volume II], page 69; retrieved December 11, 2016</ref> Kemnitzer''' (November 13, 1928 in [[Pasadena, California]]<ref name=Gate>[http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Luis-Kemnitzer-professor-and-social-activist-2503701.php Luis Kemnitzer -- professor and social activist], by Marianne Costantinou, at the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]''; published February 22, 2006; retrieved April 30, 2014</ref>– February 17, 2006) was an American [[anthropologist]] known for his social and political activism.

From 1967 to 1994,<ref name=Memo>[http://www.sfsu.edu/news/cmemo/spring06/feb27.htm Campus Memo], volume 53, number 23 (item 4 - In memoriam: Luis Kemnitzer), at [[San Francisco State University]]; published February 27, 2006; retrieved May 2, 2014</ref> Kemnitzer was a professor at [[San Francisco State University]], where in 1969 he taught that institution's first course in [[Native American studies|American Indian Studies]].<ref name=SFSU>[http://xpress.sfsu.edu/archives/breaking/005395.html Grammy winning SF State professor dies: Lung cancer takes former anthropology professor Dr. Luis Kemnitzer], by Paulette Bleam, at [[San Francisco State University]]; published February 22, 2006; retrieved April 30, 2014</ref><ref>[http://kuscholarworks.ku.edu/dspace/bitstream/1808/5763/1/ins.v02.n1.11-20.pdf From Activism to Academics: The Evolution of American Indian Studies at San Francisco State 1968-2001], by Joely De La Torre; Indigenous Nations Studies Journal, Vol. 2, No. 1, Spring 2001; p 11-21</ref> In this role, Kemnitzer visited [[Alcatraz Island]] during its [[occupation of Alcatraz|occupation]]—which had been partially planned in his classroom,<ref name=Johnson>[https://books.google.com/books?id=3M6Nhi5Pu1EC&pg=PA51 The Occupation of Alcatraz Island: Indian Self-determination and the Rise of Indian Activism], by Troy R. Johnson; published 1996 by [[University of Illinois Press]] (via [[Google Books]]); page 51</ref> and among whose participants were some of his students<ref name=Gate/> (including [[Richard Oakes (activist)|Richard Oakes]])<ref name=Johnson/> — to provide logistical advice on how to set up educational programs for Native American children on the island.<ref>"Indians ask school on Alcatraz", in ''[[the Arizona Republic]]'', page 87; December 4, 1969</ref>

== Life and work ==

Kemnitzer began his academic career in the 1940s, studying [[public health]] at the [[University of California, Berkeley]], but withdrew to become a [[brakeman]] on the [[Southern Pacific Railroad]].<ref name="Gate" /> His experiences in the labor force led him to join the [[Communist Party USA]].<ref name="Gate" /> In the 1960s, he earned his doctorate in anthropology from the [[University of Pennsylvania]],<ref name="SFSU" /> after writing a dissertation based on his experiences living among the [[Oglala Lakota]] on the [[Pine Ridge Indian Reservation]].<ref name="Gate" /> He subsequently became director of the Lakota Language and Culture Center.<ref>[http://www.human2human.org/lakota/luis.html Luis Kemnitzer], at the Lakota Language and Culture Center; published 2006; retrieved May 2, 2014</ref> His published research included studies of [[syncretism]] among the Lakota;<ref>[http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/00141844.1970.9981023?journalCode=retn20#.U2OtJ1fqhYQ The cultural provenience of objects used in Yuwipi: A modern Teton Dakota healing ritual], by Luis S. Kemnitzer; in ''Ethnos: Journal of Anthropology''; Vol. 35, Issue 1-4, 1970; page 40-75; DOI: 10.1080/00141844.1970.9981023</ref> railroad workers' [[time perception]];<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/3317384?uid=3739464&uid=2&uid=3737720&uid=4&sid=21103955716347 Another View of Time and the Railroader], by Luis S. Kemnitzer; in ''[[Anthropological Quarterly]]'', Vol. 50, No. 1, Golden Anniversary Special Issue on Industrial Ethnology (Jan., 1977), pp. 25-29, via [[JSTOR]]</ref> and [[needle exchange programme]]s.<ref>[http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/an.1994.35.3.4.2/abstract Needle Exchange: East vs West], by Luis S. Kemnitzer and Moher Downing; <!-- yes, the page at Wiley says "Mother"; that's a typo.--> in ''Anthropology News''; Volume 35, Issue 3, page 4, March 1994; doi: 10.1111/an.1994.35.3.4.2</ref>

As an activist, Kemnitzer helped establish the first needle exchange programme in [[San Francisco]]'s [[Tenderloin, San Francisco|Tenderloin district]];<ref name="SFSU" /> and attempted to distribute [[condom]]s to [[Bohemian Grove]] attendees.<ref name="grove">[http://articles.latimes.com/1987-07-13/news/mn-2063_1_protester The State], at the [[Los Angeles Times]]; published July 13, 1987; retrieved April 30, 2014</ref> In 2005, he and his partner Moher Downing posed naked for the 2006 "Hotties of [[harm reduction|Harm Reduction]]" calendar; the 2007 calendar was dedicated to his memory.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20081120101500/http://www.hottiesofharmreduction.org/2007/about.html About the Hotties Calendar Project], at Hotties of Harm Reduction (via [[archive.org]]); published 2007; archived November 20, 2008; retrieved December 27, 2016</ref>

In 1997, Kemnitzer, who had for many years been an avid [[Gramophone record|record]] collector,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=dujx_t8lRAIC&dq=%22luis+kemnitzer%22+%22american+folk%22&source=gbs_navlinks_s Harry Smith: The Avant-garde in the American Vernacular], by Andrew Perchuk and Rani Singh; published 2010 by Getty Publications; page 249; "Luis Kemnitzer, like Smith an inveterate record collector"</ref> helped create the [[liner notes]] for the [[Smithsonian Folkways Recordings]] reissue of ''[[Anthology of American Folk Music]]''<ref name="Smithsonian">[http://www.folkways.si.edu/anthology-of-american-folk-music/african-american-music-blues-old-time/music/album/smithsonian Smithsonian Folkways - Anthology of American Folk Music], at [[Smithsonian Folkways]]; retrieved April 30, 2014</ref> (originally compiled by [[Harry Everett Smith]], with whom Kemnitzer had been friends).<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/40644108 Collecting, Collage, and Alchemy: The Harry Smith ''Anthology of American Folk Music'' as Art and Cultural Intervention], by Kevin M. Moist; in ''American Studies''; Vol. 48, No. 4 (Winter 2007), pp. 111-127; via [[JSTOR]]</ref> He subsequently shared in the 1998 [[Grammy Award for Best Album Notes]].<ref name="Gate" />

